'''Stéphane Nomis''' (born 23 October 1970) is a professional [[France|French]] [[judo]]ka.
{{Infobox martial artist | name = Stéphane Nomis | other_names = | image = Snomis.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Stéphane Nomis | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|10|23}} | birth_place = [[Versailles (city)|Versailles]], [[France]] | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | nationality = [[France|French]] | height_m = | weight_lb = | weight_class = [[Middleweight]] | reach = | style = [[Judo]] | stance = | fighting_out_of = | team = | rank = [[Black belt (martial arts)|Black belt]] in [[Judo]] (4th Dan) | years_active = 1995-1999 | occupation = }}
==Sporting career== From 1990 to 1999, he trains as a professional judoka at [[INSEP]] and is part of the France national team under the direction of René Rambier at the [[FFJDA|French Federation of Judo]]. He trains with [[David Douillet]], [[Djamel Bouras]] and [[Larbi Benboudaoud]]. Nomis earned medals in many championships, including a gold medal at the French Championships and a bronze medal at the [[European Judo Championships|European Championships]]. He managed to reach the finals of the French championships, and after a bronze medal at the tournament in Paris, he qualified for the European Championships for the second time. He brought his career to an end in 1999.
