[[File:WelshDresserBedfordMuseum.JPG|thumb|A Welsh dresser on display in [[Bedford Museum & Art Gallery|Bedford Museum]]]] A '''Welsh dresser''' ([[British English]]) or a '''china hutch''' ([[American English]]), sometimes known as a '''kitchen dresser''' or '''pewter cupboard''', is a piece of wooden furniture consisting of drawers and [[cupboards]] in the lower part, with shelves and perhaps a [[sideboard]] on top. Traditionally, it is a utilitarian piece of furniture used to store and display [[crockery]], [[Tableware|silverware]] and [[pewter]]-ware, but is also used to display general ornaments.<ref>[http://www.ldoceonline.com/dictionary/Welsh-dresser Welsh dresser] Longman dictionary of contemporary English, Accessed 22 April 2010</ref><ref>[http://dictionary.reverso.net/english-definition/Welsh%20dresser Welsh dresser] Free dictionary cites: the English Collins Dictionary - English Definition & Thesaurus</ref><ref>Percy W. Blandford. ''A home full of furniture: 79 more furniture projects for every room'', Tab Books, 1990, {{ISBN|0-8306-7500-0}}, {{ISBN|978-0-8306-7500-5}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=_7Oekj_W0w0C&q=%22welsh+dresser%22+%22china+hutch%22&dq=%22welsh+dresser%22+%22china+hutch%22&hl=en&ei=dtDQS5PiBYyA7QPt6p2WDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAA p. 335] "Welsh dresser (china hutch), 158&ndash;168"</ref>
[[File:Dresser (PSF).png|thumb|A plain Welsh dresser]] Originally, a dresser was located in the kitchen and was a utilitarian piece of furniture where meat and other food was dressed or prepared, while prepared food was placed on sideboards in the dining room ready to be served.<ref>{{cite book |last=Davis|first=Karen|year=2001|title=More than a meal: the turkey in history, myth, ritual, and reality |edition=illustrated |publisher=Lantern Books |isbn=1-930051-88-3|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=NxHN2RKmI3gC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA58#v=onepage&q&f=false 58] |quote='dresser' meaning the table on which meat and other foods were prepare}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rightpricefurniture.co.uk/furniture/nd40-ns40-devonshire-new-solid-oak-4ft-6in-dresser-complete.aspx |title=2601 Dressers and Sideboards A brief History|publisher=RightPriceFurniture|accessdate=19 November 2010 }}</ref> They could be modified to suit local needs; for example, dressers in the Scottish Highlands may have a "porridge drawer"&mdash;a tin lined drawer into which freshly made [[porridge]] was emptied and left to cool. When cold, slices of the porridge could be cut out and taken out of the house for later consumption.<ref>{{cite web|author=BBC staff|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/highlands_and_islands/7665854.stm |title=Secret weapon wins porridge title|date=12 October 2008 |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Gradually the purely utilitarian function of the dresser was supplemented with other functions, such as a means of displaying the best crockery in a farmhouse. Once it became a means of display the dresser could also be found in dining rooms where it served as sideboard and a place to store and display dinner ware.<ref>{{cite book |first=Mary Ellen |last=Snodgrass |year=2004 |title=Encyclopedia of kitchen history|edition=2, illustrated|publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=1-57958-380-6 |page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D7IhN7lempUC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA128#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref> In the 19th century various different styles of ceramics would evolve to fill the plate racks of the Welsh dressers of [[Wales]] and to meet the needs of the Welsh market. Furthermore, many local traditions of what constitutes the proper care and display of the items on a Welsh dresser would come to assume an important role in the culture of North Wales in particular.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dai Davies|url=http://Welshdresser.org.uk/ |title=History of the Welsh Dresser|date=9 September 2012}}</ref>
==See also== {{wiktionary}} * [[Chest of drawers]] * [[Hoosier cabinet]] * [[Hutch (furniture)]] *[[Sideboard]]
